            "answer_text": "It's never totally new in the sense that it combines earlier ideas, but nonetheless that is how small and big advances happen. My brain keeps spinning, sometimes alone (when I wake up, usually), sometimes in group (brainstorming, discussion), and it looks for new ways to put together the pieces of the puzzle. It all happens behind the veil of consciousness. Just asking yourself a question starts your brain spinning, sometimes for minutes, sometimes for days and months. The puzzle pieces are the pieces of evidence we observe, and the picture is one allowing us to understand the world around us. Sometimes, a new idea combines many pieces and we feel the intense pleasure of Eureka, epiphany, as so many pieces finally seem to fit perfectly together. Then we feel compelled to share the idea and check it out, test it against more experiments and against the test of logic (e.g., trying to prove a theorem). Many ideas turn out to be failures, and one has to accept that in order to continue letting out more ideas from one's brain. We get emotionally attached to our ideas and it may be difficult to let go of them. Sometimes, the idea that comes to us is not just new, but it goes against common beliefs (both those we received from others and those we incorrectly forged ourselves). We all wear blinders due to false beliefs, that make it difficult to accept groundbreaking ideas when they come. That is where it is good to remind ourselves that almost nothing is for sure, and that if we don't follow our intuition we will never make those major discoveries, because new ideas mostly come from the underground of our brain, and show up as \"intuitions\" and mental pictures springing to life. To take advantage of that source of creativity, we have to believe in ourselves, and at the same time accept that most of the time, our ideas can be wrong. ",
